title: A Phase 3, Double-blind, Randomized Study of RVT-101 Versus Placebo When Added to Existing Stable Donepezil Treatment in Subjects With Mild to Moderate Alzheimer's Disease
description_brief: This study seeks to confirm a demonstrated treatment effect of intepirdine (RVT-101) as an adjunctive therapy to donepezil for the treatment of subjects with Alzheimer's disease.
description_detailed: This Phase 3 study seeks to confirm a demonstrated treatment effect of intepirdine (RVT-101) on both cognition and activities of daily living when added to stable donepezil treatment in subjects with mild-to-moderate Alzheimer's disease after 24 weeks of double-blind treatment. This study will also provide further information on the safety and tolerability of the 35-mg dose of intepirdine (RVT-101) when used in combination with donepezil compared to donepezil alone. This study is being conducted under the agreement of a Special Protocol Assessment by FDA. Subjects completing this study will be eligible to enroll in a 12 month open-label study of RVT-101 (RVT-101-3002) in which concomitant medications for the treatment of Alzheimer's disease including memantine will be allowed.

participantFlowModule.preAssignmentDetails: 2173 participants signed consent and were screened for participation. Of these, 1470 entered a 3-week single-blind placebo run-in period with treatment with placebo qd + stable dose of donepezil 5 or 10 mg qd. There was an overlap between the participants from the run-in period and the participants that were randomized during the treatment period.

outcomeMeasures.title: Clinical Global Impression of Change - Plus Caregiver Interview (CIBIC+) Score at Week 24
outcomeMeasures.description: The CIBIC+ assessment measures the global functioning of the subject. The CIBIC+ is scored as a seven-point categorical rating, ranging from a score of 1 (indicating "very much improved"), to a score of 4 (indicating "no change"), or to a score of 7 (indicating "very much worse.") Lower CIBIC+ scores indicate better (more desirable) function
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: ITT population at the Week 24 timepoint

outcomeMeasures.title: The Dependence Scale (DS) Score Change From Baseline to Week 24
outcomeMeasures.description: The DS measures the amount of assistance patients with dementia require in performing daily activities. The scale consists of 13 items, representing a range of severity from mild to severe levels of dependency. The score range is from 0 to 15 with higher scores indicating greater dependency.

outcomeMeasures.title: Neuropsychiatric Inventory (NPI) Score Change From Baseline to Week 24
outcomeMeasures.description: The NPI is a behavior rating scale composed of a 12-item structured interview of the caregiver that is scored from 0 to 144 (the higher the score, the greater the psychiatric disturbance). It assesses 12 behavioral disturbances occurring in dementia patients: delusions, hallucinations, agitation, dysphoria, anxiety, apathy, irritability, euphoria, disinhibition, aberrant motor activity, night-time behavior disturbances, and eating disturbances. Both the frequency and the severity of each behavior are determined.

outcomeMeasures.title: ADAS-Cog-13 Score Change From Baseline to Week 24
outcomeMeasures.description: 13-item ADAS-Cog assesses a range of cognitive abilities including memory, comprehension, orientation in time and place, and spontaneous speech. Most items are evaluated by tests, but some are dependent on clinician ratings on a 5-point scale. The ADAS-Cog-13 is the ADAS-Cog-11 with 2 additional items: delayed word recall and total digit cancellation. Scores for the ADAS-Cog-13 range from 0 to 85 with higher scores indicating greater dysfunction.

explanation_target: Reason: The intervention is intepirdine (RVT-101, also SB-742457), an orally administered small-molecule antagonist of the serotonin 5-HT6 receptor. 5-HT6 antagonists are designed to increase central neurotransmitter (e.g., acetylcholine) release and thereby improve cognition, typically used as adjunctive cognitive therapy rather than targeting core AD pathology (amyloid/tau). citeturn0search0turn0search5

Act: Key trial details — Phase 3 MINDSET evaluated 35 mg/day intepirdine versus placebo added to stable donepezil in mild-to-moderate AD to test effects on cognition and activities of daily living; intepirdine is described in the literature and registries as a 5-HT6 receptor antagonist (small molecule). citeturn0search4turn0search0

Web search results supporting drug identity and mechanism: intepirdine = RVT-101 = SB-742457; mechanism = selective 5-HT6 receptor antagonist; development included phase 2 and the phase 3 MINDSET adjunct-to-donepezil study (which ultimately failed to show benefit). citeturn0search5turn0search0turn0search4

Reflect: Classification rationale — intepirdine is a small-molecule neurotransmitter-modulating agent intended to improve cognitive function when added to acetylcholinesterase inhibitor therapy, not a biologic nor an agent that targets amyloid/tau pathology or primarily treats neuropsychiatric symptoms. Therefore it fits the 'cognitive enhancer' category. I note the drug is a small molecule, but its therapeutic aim (enhancing cognition via 5-HT6 antagonism) places it in the cognitive enhancer category rather than 'disease-targeted small molecule.' citeturn0search0turn0search5
explanation_agent: Reason: The investigational drug intepirdine (RVT-101; SB-742457) is a selective antagonist of the serotonin 5-HT6 receptor intended to increase central neurotransmitter (e.g., acetylcholine, glutamate) release to improve cognition as an adjunct to donepezil — this mechanism directly implicates neurotransmitter receptor modulation rather than amyloid, tau, inflammation, or other CADRO domains. citeturn0search4turn0search1

Act: Extracted trial details and mechanism — Phase 3 MINDSET tested 35 mg/day intepirdine versus placebo added to stable donepezil in mild-to-moderate AD; intepirdine is consistently described in the literature and registries as a 5‑HT6 receptor antagonist (small molecule). These sources document the drug identity, receptor target, and the MINDSET trial design/results. citeturn0search0turn0search1turn0search4

Web search results supporting drug identity and mechanism: PubMed/Wiley summaries and trial reports confirm intepirdine = RVT-101 = SB-742457 and mechanism = selective 5‑HT6 receptor antagonist; MINDSET was a global Phase 3 adjunct-to-donepezil study that failed to show significant benefit. citeturn0search0turn0search1turn0search4

Reflect: Classification rationale — because the drug’s primary action is modulation of a neurotransmitter receptor (5‑HT6) to produce symptomatic cognitive enhancement rather than targeting core AD pathologies (amyloid or tau) or other biological processes, the most specific CADRO match is D) Neurotransmitter Receptors. There is no strong evidence here of multiple distinct biological targets that would require 'R) Multi-target', nor is this a non‑therapeutic/diagnostic intervention, so 'D' is the appropriate classification. citeturn0search4turn0search0
